<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Shadow Effects Example</title>
    <style>
        /* Body styling */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f4f4f4;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
            text-align: center;
        }

        /* Header with text-shadow */
        h1 {
            color: #333;
            text-shadow: 2px 2px 5px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4); /* Horizontal, vertical, blur radius, color */
            font-size: 3em;
        }

        /* Box-shadow for content containers */
        .container {
            background-color: white;
            padding: 40px;
            margin: 20px auto;
            width: 80%;
            max-width: 600px;
            box-shadow: 5px 5px 15px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3); /* Horizontal, vertical, blur, spread, color */
            border-radius: 10px; /* Rounded corners */
        }

        .container h2 {
            color: #4CAF50;
            text-shadow: 2px 2px 4px rgba(0, 150, 0, 0.6); /* Green shadow */
        }

        .container p {
            color: #555;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            line-height: 1.6;
        }

        /* Button with shadow */
        .button {
            background-color: #ff5722;
            color: white;
            padding: 15px 30px;
            text-decoration: none;
            font-size: 1.2em;
            border-radius: 5px;
            display: inline-block;
            box-shadow: 3px 3px 8px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4); /* Shadow under the button */
        }

        .button:hover {
            background-color: #ff784e;
            box-shadow: 3px 3px 12px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6); /* Larger shadow on hover */
        }

    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <!-- Header Section with Text Shadow -->
    <h1>Shadow Effects in Web Design</h1>

    <!-- First container with box shadow -->
    <div class="container">
        <h2>What is Shadow in CSS?</h2>
        <p>
            CSS provides two types of shadows: text-shadow and box-shadow. Text-shadow is used to add shadow to text,
            and box-shadow is used to add shadow to boxes (like divs, images, etc.). These effects give depth to your
            design, making elements appear more realistic.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Second container with box shadow -->
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Box Shadow Example</h2>
        <p>
            The container you're seeing now has a box-shadow effect applied to it. You can adjust the size, spread, and
            color of the shadow to create various effects.
        </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Button with shadow -->
    <a href="#" class="button">Click Me</a>

</body>
</html>
